Peel and grate the @garlic clove{3} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @bell pepper{1} and discard the core and seeds. Slice into thin strips.

Pop a deep #saucepan{} (with a #tight-fitting lid{}) on medium heat. Melt in the @butter{20%g} (see pantry for amount).

Once hot, add half the garlic and stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir the @basmati rice{150%g} into the garlic and cook until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Add @salt{1/4%tsp} and the @water{300%ml} for the rice (see pantry for amount) into the pan and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While the rice cooks, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{1%pack}, @diced chorizo{90%g} and sliced pepper to the pan. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Fry until the chicken is browned all over and the pepper is tender, ~{5-6%minutes}. Turn occasionally.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Stir the @Central American style spice mix{1%sachet} and remaining garlic into the chicken. Fry for ~{30%seconds}.

Pour in the @finely chopped tomatoes with onion and garlic{1/2%carton}, @chicken stock paste{10%g}, @sugar{1%tsp} and the @water{100%ml} for the sauce (see pantry for both amounts), stirring to combine.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until the chicken is cooked and the sauce has thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once the chicken is cooked and the sauce has thickened, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then remove from the heat.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{}.

Share the garlic rice between your #bowls{} and spoon the chicken and chorizo stew on top.

Top with a spoonful of @soured cream{75%g} to finish.

Enjoy!